"# Chapter 2: Velocity

Movement begins with a single fact: **something is going somewhere**. Not arriving yet—we'll learn arrival in Chapter 3—just *going*. A constant direction, a steady speed, the simplest possible motion. A petal drifts across the frame at walking pace. A courier cycles down the avenue. A satellite crosses the night sky. They all share one quality: **velocity**.

Velocity is the second atom of motion. In Chapter 1 we learned to place the sprite in the world—`entity/set-pos!` gave her coordinates, a fixed spot. Now we give her *intention*: a direction and a rate. She moves. The world unfolds.

This chapter drills one idea until it's in your fingers: `entity/set-vel!` paired with `world/step`. We'll vary the scenario forty times—different speeds, different headings, different reasons to move—but the kernel stays the same. By the end, you'll feel the difference between a drift and a dart, a crawl and a coast. You'll know how to send something across the frame and *mean it*.

---

## The first move

Here is the sprite, standing still at the origin. We spawn her, take one snapshot of the world, and report her position. Nothing moves yet.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(world/step 0.016)
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: A single frame. The sprite stands at (0, 0). The coordinate grid is visible, soft gray lines. No motion.]

Now we give her velocity—two units rightward per second, nothing vertical—and step the world forward for one frame (about 1/60th of a second). She moves a tiny bit.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 2 0)
(world/step 0.016)
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite has shifted slightly to the right. Her velocity vector is drawn as a faint arrow pointing right. The coordinate readout shows (~0.032, 0).]

The position changed. That's motion. Step the world ten times and she travels ten times as far.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 2 0)
(let loop ((n 10))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite is now visibly to the right, around (0.32, 0). A faint trail of dots shows her path—perfectly horizontal.]

This is the foundation. Everything that moves in the sprite's world will use this pair: `set-vel!` to declare the motion, `world/step` to make time pass.

---

## Direction

Velocity is a *vector*—two numbers, x and y. The first number is horizontal speed (positive = rightward, negative = leftward). The second is vertical (positive = upward, negative = downward). We can send the sprite in any direction.

Moving upward at one unit per second:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 0 1)
(let loop ((n 20))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite has moved upward. Her trail is vertical. Position is near (0, 0.32).]

Leftward, fast:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero -5 0)
(let loop ((n 20))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite is well to the left, around (-1.6, 0). The trail is a straight horizontal line pointing left.]

Diagonal—up and to the right:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 3 2)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite has moved northeast. The trail is a clean diagonal. Position is around (1.44, 0.96).]

The ratio of the two numbers sets the angle. The *magnitude*—how big the numbers are—sets the speed.

---

## Speed

Speed is how far something travels per second. A velocity of `(3, 0)` means three units per second horizontally. A velocity of `(0, -4)` means four units per second downward. The actual *speed* (the length of the velocity vector) can be calculated with the Pythagorean theorem: `sqrt(vx^2 + vy^2)`.

A slow drift:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define petal (world/spawn 'petal 0 5))
(entity/set-vel! petal 0.5 -0.3)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos petal)
```

[VISUAL: A cherry-blossom petal floats gently down and to the right. The trail is long and shallow. Position is around (0.48, 4.71).]

A dart:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define arrow (world/spawn 'arrow -3 0))
(entity/set-vel! arrow 12 0)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos arrow)
```

[VISUAL: An arrow streaks across the screen. The trail is short because it moves so fast. Position is around (2.76, 0).]

A ball tossed at 45 degrees, medium speed:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define ball (world/spawn 'ball 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! ball 4 4)
(let loop ((n 40))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos ball)
```

[VISUAL: A ball moves diagonally up and right. The trail is a perfect straight line at 45°. Position is around (2.56, 2.56).]

Notice: the motion is *linear*. No curve, no slow-down, no arrival. Just constant velocity. That's what this chapter drills. Curves and easing come later.

---

## Many entities, each with their own velocity

The world can hold many things, each moving independently. Spawn three entities, give each a different velocity, step the world forward. They all move.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'dot -2 0))
(define b (world/spawn 'dot 0 2))
(define c (world/spawn 'dot 2 -1))
(entity/set-vel! a 1 0)
(entity/set-vel! b 0 -1)
(entity/set-vel! c -0.5 0.5)
(let loop ((n 50))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos a) (entity/pos b) (entity/pos c))
```

[VISUAL: Three dots move in different directions. A moves right, B moves down, C moves left and up. Their trails cross and diverge. Final positions printed below.]

Each entity carries its own velocity. The world doesn't care if they're related—it just steps them all forward.

---

## Changing velocity mid-flight

Velocity isn't permanent. You can call `set-vel!` again at any time. The entity instantly adopts the new vector.

Start moving right, then halfway through, change to moving up:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero -3 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 3 0)
(let loop ((n 25))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/set-vel! hero 0 2)
(let loop ((n 25))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's trail has a sharp right-angle corner. She moves horizontally, then vertically. No curve—instant direction change. Final position around (1.2, 0.8).]

This is how you build more complex motion: a *sequence* of constant-velocity segments. Real-world motion is rarely perfectly linear, but linear segments are the building blocks. (In Chapter 3 we'll learn to *blend* between velocities smoothly—that's easing. Here we just snap.)

---

## Stopping

Setting velocity to zero stops the entity. It stays wherever it was when you zeroed it.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! hero 2 1)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/set-vel! hero 0 0)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite moves diagonally up and right, then her trail ends abruptly. She stays in place for the second half of the animation. Final position around (0.96, 0.48).]

This is the simplest kind of \"halt.\" No deceleration, no settle—just instant stillness. (We'll learn weight and settle in Chapter 6.)

---

## Reversing

Negating the velocity sends the entity back the way it came.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define courier (world/spawn 'courier -4 0))
(entity/set-vel! courier 4 0)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(let ((v (entity/vel courier)))
  (entity/set-vel! courier (- (car v)) (- (cadr v))))
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos courier)
```

[VISUAL: A courier cycles right, then immediately turns around and cycles left at the same speed. The trail is a straight line, right then left. Final position back near (-4, 0).]

Notice we read the current velocity with `entity/vel` and negate both components. The entity returns along the exact same path.

---

## Speed as a single number

Sometimes you want to set a speed (a scalar) and a heading (an angle), not raw x/y components. Scheme gives us `dcos` and `dsin` (deterministic trig functions) to convert polar to Cartesian.

Move at speed 5, heading 30 degrees (measured counterclockwise from the positive x-axis):

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(let ((speed 5)
      (angle (* 30 (/ PI 180))))
  (entity/set-vel! hero (* speed (dcos angle)) (* speed (dsin angle))))
(let loop ((n 40))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite moves at a shallow upward angle. The trail is a straight line tilted 30° above horizontal. Final position around (3.46, 1.28).]

Same speed, heading 120 degrees:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 0 0))
(let ((speed 5)
      (angle (* 120 (/ PI 180))))
  (entity/set-vel! hero (* speed (dcos angle)) (* speed (dsin angle))))
(let loop ((n 40))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos hero)
```

[VISUAL: The sprite moves up and to the left at 120°. Final position around (-1.60, 2.77).]

This is useful when you're thinking in *directions* (north, northeast, etc.) rather than component speeds.

---

## Orbits (a preview)

If you change velocity *every frame* to always point perpendicular to the current position (relative to a center), the entity orbits. This is a sneak peek—Chapter 8 will drill oscillation thoroughly—but it shows how velocity can be dynamic.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define moon (world/spawn 'moon 3 0))
(let loop ((n 120))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((pos (entity/pos moon))
           (x (car pos))
           (y (cadr pos))
           (angle (datan2 y x))
           (speed 2))
      (entity/set-vel! moon (* speed (- (dsin angle))) (* speed (dcos angle)))
      (world/step 0.016)
      (loop (- n 1)))))
(entity/pos moon)
```

[VISUAL: A moon traces a circular orbit around the origin. The trail is a perfect circle, radius 3. Final position is back near (3, 0).]

Every frame we calculate the angle from the origin, then set velocity perpendicular to that. The moon goes in a circle. This is velocity used as a *steering* mechanism—recalculated continuously. Most of this chapter uses velocity as a one-time declaration, but it's good to see the dynamic case early.

---

## Relative velocity

Entities don't know about each other unless you tell them. If two entities have the same velocity, they stay the same distance apart—they're moving together, like two birds in a flock.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define bird-a (world/spawn 'bird -2 1))
(define bird-b (world/spawn 'bird -2 -1))
(entity/set-vel! bird-a 3 0.5)
(entity/set-vel! bird-b 3 0.5)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos bird-a) (entity/pos bird-b))
```

[VISUAL: Two birds fly in parallel. Their trails are identical diagonals, separated by a constant vertical gap. Final positions are around (0.88, 1.48) and (0.88, -0.52).]

If one is slightly faster, they gradually separate:

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define bird-a (world/spawn 'bird -2 1))
(define bird-b (world/spawn 'bird -2 -1))
(entity/set-vel! bird-a 3 0.5)
(entity/set-vel! bird-b 3.2 0.5)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos bird-a) (entity/pos bird-b))
```

[VISUAL: Two birds fly at nearly the same angle, but bird-b gradually pulls ahead. The trails diverge slightly. Final x-positions differ by about 0.19 units.]

This is how you orchestrate groups—give each member a velocity, vary them slightly, and the formation shifts.

---

## Patrol: back and forth

A common pattern: move right until you hit a boundary, then reverse and move left. Repeat forever. This is a *state machine* built on velocity changes.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define guard (world/spawn 'guard -5 0))
(entity/set-vel! guard 2 0)
(let loop ((n 200))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((x (car (entity/pos guard))))
      (when (> x 5)
        (entity/set-vel! guard -2 0))
      (when (< x -5)
        (entity/set-vel! guard 2 0)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos guard)
```

[VISUAL: A guard paces back and forth between x = -5 and x = 5. The trail is a horizontal line segment, retraced multiple times. Final position is somewhere in the patrol range.]

Every frame we check position. If past the right boundary, flip velocity to leftward. If past the left boundary, flip to rightward. The guard marches back and forth forever.

---

## Chase (constant velocity toward a target)

Calculate the vector from chaser to target, normalize it (make it length 1), scale by desired speed, and set that as velocity. The chaser moves toward the target at constant speed.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define hero (world/spawn 'hero 5 5))
(define cat (world/spawn 'cat -3 -2))
(entity/set-vel! hero 0 0)
(let ((chase-speed 3))
  (let loop ((n 60))
    (when (> n 0)
      (let* ((cat-pos (entity/pos cat))
             (hero-pos (entity/pos hero))
             (dx (- (car hero-pos) (car cat-pos)))
             (dy (- (cadr hero-pos) (cadr cat-pos)))
             (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
        (when (> dist 0.1)
          (entity/set-vel! cat 
                           (* chase-speed (/ dx dist)) 
                           (* chase-speed (/ dy dist))))
        (world/step 0.016)
        (loop (- n 1)))))
(entity/pos cat))
```

[VISUAL: A cat moves toward the sprite in a straight line. The sprite is stationary. The cat's trail is a ray from (-3, -2) toward (5, 5). Final position is much closer to the sprite.]

This is a *homing* behavior. Every frame we recalculate the direction to the target and set velocity along that line. (If we only set it *once* at the start, the cat would move in a straight line but wouldn't adjust if the sprite moved. Here the sprite is still, but the pattern generalizes.)

---

## Flee (constant velocity away from a threat)

The opposite of chase: calculate the vector *from* threat *to* entity, normalize, scale.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define fox (world/spawn 'fox 0 0))
(define rabbit (world/spawn 'rabbit 2 1))
(entity/set-vel! fox 0 0)
(let ((flee-speed 4))
  (let loop ((n 50))
    (when (> n 0)
      (let* ((rabbit-pos (entity/pos rabbit))
             (fox-pos (entity/pos fox))
             (dx (- (car rabbit-pos) (car fox-pos)))
             (dy (- (cadr rabbit-pos) (cadr fox-pos)))
             (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
        (when (> dist 0.1)
          (entity/set-vel! rabbit 
                           (* flee-speed (/ dx dist)) 
                           (* flee-speed (/ dy dist))))
        (world/step 0.016)
        (loop (- n 1)))))
(entity/pos rabbit))
```

[VISUAL: A rabbit flees from a stationary fox. The trail is a straight line pointing away from the fox. Final position is much farther from the origin, around (5.2, 2.6).]

Flee is just chase with the vector negated (or equivalently, swapped source and target).

---

## Wander (velocity that changes randomly)

Add a small random perturbation to velocity every few frames. The entity drifts in a lazy, unpredictable path.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define leaf (world/spawn 'leaf 0 3))
(entity/set-vel! leaf 1 -0.5)
(let loop ((n 100) (counter 0))
  (when (> n 0)
    (when (= (modulo counter 10) 0)
      (let ((vx (car (entity/vel leaf)))
            (vy (cadr (entity/vel leaf))))
        (entity/set-vel! leaf 
                         (+ vx (* 0.3 (- (random) 0.5)))
                         (+ vy (* 0.3 (- (random) 0.5))))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1) (+ counter 1))))
(entity/pos leaf)
```

[VISUAL: A leaf drifts downward with a gentle, meandering path. The trail has soft curves (from the frequent direction changes). Final position is down and somewhat to the right, but the path isn't straight.]

Every 10 frames we nudge the velocity by a small random amount. The leaf wanders. This is how you get organic, unpredictable motion from simple velocity changes.

---

## Formation flight

Three entities in a V-formation, all moving together. Set their velocities to be identical, but spawn them at offset positions.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define lead (world/spawn 'bird 0 0))
(define left-wing (world/spawn 'bird -1 -0.8))
(define right-wing (world/spawn 'bird 1 -0.8))
(entity/set-vel! lead 3 1)
(entity/set-vel! left-wing 3 1)
(entity/set-vel! right-wing 3 1)
(let loop ((n 70))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos lead) (entity/pos left-wing) (entity/pos right-wing))
```

[VISUAL: Three birds fly in a V. Their trails are parallel. The formation stays rigid. Final positions maintain the V-shape offset.]

Because all three have the same velocity, the distances between them never change. The entire formation translates as a unit.

---

## Lanes (parallel traffic)

Five entities moving horizontally at different heights, like cars in lanes. Different speeds per lane.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define lane1 (world/spawn 'car -5 3))
(define lane2 (world/spawn 'car -6 1.5))
(define lane3 (world/spawn 'car -4 0))
(define lane4 (world/spawn 'car -5.5 -1.5))
(define lane5 (world/spawn 'car -7 -3))
(entity/set-vel! lane1 2.5 0)
(entity/set-vel! lane2 3.0 0)
(entity/set-vel! lane3 2.0 0)
(entity/set-vel! lane4 2.8 0)
(entity/set-vel! lane5 2.2 0)
(let loop ((n 90))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos lane1) (entity/pos lane2) (entity/pos lane3) (entity/pos lane4) (entity/pos lane5))
```

[VISUAL: Five horizontal lanes of traffic. Each car moves at a slightly different speed. The faster ones pull ahead, the slower ones lag. Final x-positions vary by about 1.4 units.]

This is how you orchestrate a *flow*—many entities, same general direction, slightly varied speeds to break up the rhythm.

---

## Crossing paths

Two entities approach from opposite sides, pass through each other (no collision yet—we haven't wired that), and continue on.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'walker -4 0))
(define b (world/spawn 'walker 4 0))
(entity/set-vel! a 2 0)
(entity/set-vel! b -2 0)
(let loop ((n 80))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos a) (entity/pos b))
```

[VISUAL: Two walkers approach from left and right, meet in the middle, pass through each other, and continue. Their trails cross at (0, 0). Final positions are swapped: a is on the right, b is on the left.]

They ghost through each other because we haven't enabled collision. But the *intent* is clear—they're on a collision course, moving at the same speed in opposite directions.

---

## Spiral (velocity rotates over time)

Rotate the velocity vector a tiny bit every frame. The entity spirals outward (if speed increases) or inward (if speed decreases), or in a circle (if speed stays constant).

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define particle (world/spawn 'particle 2 0))
(entity/set-vel! particle 0 2)
(let loop ((n 150))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((v (entity/vel particle))
           (vx (car v))
           (vy (cadr v))
           (angle (datan2 vy vx))
           (speed (dsqrt (+ (* vx vx) (* vy vy))))
           (new-angle (+ angle 0.05)))
      (entity/set-vel! particle 
                       (* speed (dcos new-angle)) 
                       (* speed (dsin new-angle))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos particle)
```

[VISUAL: A particle spirals around the origin. The trail is a smooth logarithmic spiral. Final position is back near the starting radius, but rotated.]

Each frame we add a small angle to the velocity direction. The particle turns. This is the foundation of circular and spiral motion—velocity as a rotating vector.

---

## Conveyor belt (velocity imposed by the environment)

Imagine a region of space that *forces* a certain velocity on anything inside it. An entity enters the region and is swept along.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define crate (world/spawn 'crate -3 0))
(entity/set-vel! crate 1 0)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((x (car (entity/pos crate))))
      (if (and (> x -1) (< x 2))
          (entity/set-vel! crate 4 0)
          (when (>= x 2)
            (entity/set-vel! crate 1 0))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos crate)
```

[VISUAL: A crate approaches from the left at normal speed. When it enters the region x ∈ (-1, 2), it suddenly accelerates (the trail spacing increases). After exiting at x=2, it returns to normal speed.]

This is a *zone* effect. While inside the zone, velocity is overridden. Outside the zone, the original velocity resumes. (In a real engine you might store the original and restore it; here we just hard-code the exit velocity.)

---

## Slingshot (velocity boost at a point)

An entity passes through a specific location and receives a sudden velocity spike—like a gravitational slingshot.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define probe (world/spawn 'probe -5 -2))
(entity/set-vel! probe 3 1)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((pos (entity/pos probe))
           (x (car pos))
           (y (cadr pos))
           (dist-to-boost (dsqrt (+ (* x x) (* y y)))))
      (when (< dist-to-boost 0.5)
        (entity/set-vel! probe 6 3)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos probe)
```

[VISUAL: A probe approaches the origin at moderate speed. As it passes near (0,0), the trail spacing suddenly increases—it's been boosted. Final position is much farther than it would have been without the boost.]

The probe flies past a \"slingshot point\" at the origin. When within 0.5 units, velocity doubles. The probe zooms off.

---

## River current (velocity that varies by position)

Different parts of space impose different velocities—like a river with faster current in the middle, slower near the banks.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define raft (world/spawn 'raft -4 0))
(entity/set-vel! raft 0 0)
(let loop ((n 120))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((pos (entity/pos raft))
           (y (cadr pos))
           (current-speed (if (< (abs y) 1.0) 3.0 1.0)))
      (entity/set-vel! raft current-speed 0))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos raft)
```

[VISUAL: A raft drifts downstream. Because it stays near y=0 (the middle of the river), it moves at the fast speed (3 units/sec) the whole time. If it had drifted toward y=±2, it would slow to 1 unit/sec.]

This sets velocity based on position every frame. It's a *spatially varying field*. (Chapter 9 will introduce `world/wind!` and `world/attract!` which automate this, but here we do it manually to see the mechanism.)

---

## Drift on ice (velocity persists, no friction)

On a frictionless surface, velocity never decays. Once you push something, it glides forever.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define puck (world/spawn 'puck 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! puck 4 2)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos puck)
```

[VISUAL: A hockey puck glides across the screen in a perfectly straight line. The trail is evenly spaced—constant velocity, no slowdown. Final position is around (6.4, 3.2).]

No forces, no drag, no friction. The puck moves forever at the same speed. This is the default in our engine—velocity doesn't decay unless you add drag (we'll cover that in Chapter 6).

---

## Gradual acceleration (velocity increases each frame)

Instead of setting a fixed velocity, *add* a small amount every frame. The entity speeds up.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define rocket (world/spawn 'rocket -5 -3))
(entity/set-vel! rocket 1 0.5)
(let loop ((n 80))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((v (entity/vel rocket)))
      (entity/set-vel! rocket (+ (car v) 0.05) (+ (cadr v) 0.025)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos rocket)
```

[VISUAL: A rocket launches. The trail spacing increases over time—the rocket is accelerating. Final position is much farther than constant-velocity would reach.]

Each frame we add (0.05, 0.025) to the velocity. The rocket goes faster and faster. This is *linear acceleration*—a preview of Chapter 9's force-based motion, done here manually.

---

## Gradual deceleration (velocity shrinks each frame)

Multiply velocity by a factor less than 1 each frame. The entity slows down and eventually stops.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define sled (world/spawn 'sled -4 2))
(entity/set-vel! sled 5 0)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((v (entity/vel sled)))
      (entity/set-vel! sled (* (car v) 0.98) (* (cadr v) 0.98)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos sled)
```

[VISUAL: A sled glides to a stop. The trail spacing decreases—each frame it moves a bit less. Final position is only a few units from the start; most of the motion happened early.]

Multiplying by 0.98 each frame shaves 2% off the velocity. After many frames, velocity approaches zero. This is *exponential decay*—a simple friction model.

---

## Bouncing off walls (velocity reversal on boundary)

When the entity hits a boundary, negate the component of velocity perpendicular to the wall. It bounces.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define ball (world/spawn 'ball 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! ball 3 2)
(let loop ((n 150))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((pos (entity/pos ball))
           (x (car pos))
           (y (cadr pos))
           (v (entity/vel ball))
           (vx (car v))
           (vy (cadr v)))
      (when (or (> x 5) (< x -5))
        (entity/set-vel! ball (- vx) vy))
      (when (or (> y 3) (< y -3))
        (entity/set-vel! ball vx (- vy))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos ball)
```

[VISUAL: A ball bounces around a rectangular region. The trail has sharp angle changes at the walls—perfect reflections. The ball never loses speed (elastic collision).]

When x crosses ±5, we flip vx. When y crosses ±3, we flip vy. The ball ricochets forever at constant speed. (Real bounces lose energy; we'll add that in Chapter 7.)

---

## Follow the leader

The second entity always moves toward the first entity's *current* position. The first moves freely; the second chases.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define leader (world/spawn 'leader 0 0))
(define follower (world/spawn 'follower -3 -2))
(entity/set-vel! leader 2 1)
(let loop ((n 80))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let* ((leader-pos (entity/pos leader))
           (follower-pos (entity/pos follower))
           (dx (- (car leader-pos) (car follower-pos)))
           (dy (- (cadr leader-pos) (cadr follower-pos)))
           (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
      (when (> dist 0.1)
        (entity/set-vel! follower 
                         (* 2.5 (/ dx dist)) 
                         (* 2.5 (/ dy dist)))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos leader) (entity/pos follower))
```

[VISUAL: The leader moves in a straight line. The follower's trail curves toward the leader—it's always chasing. By the end, the follower is close behind. Final positions show the follower lagging slightly.]

The follower recalculates its velocity every frame to point at the leader's *current* position. Because the leader is also moving, the follower traces a curved path (even though its velocity is recalculated linearly each frame).

---

## Herding (many followers, one leader)

Five followers, all chasing the same leader. They converge.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define leader (world/spawn 'leader 0 3))
(entity/set-vel! leader 1 -0.5)
(define f1 (world/spawn 'follower -4 0))
(define f2 (world/spawn 'follower 4 0))
(define f3 (world/spawn 'follower 0 -3))
(define f4 (world/spawn 'follower -2 2))
(define f5 (world/spawn 'follower 2 -2))
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((leader-pos (entity/pos leader)))
      (for-each
       (lambda (f)
         (let* ((fpos (entity/pos f))
                (dx (- (car leader-pos) (car fpos)))
                (dy (- (cadr leader-pos) (cadr fpos)))
                (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
           (when (> dist 0.1)
             (entity/set-vel! f (* 2 (/ dx dist)) (* 2 (/ dy dist))))))
       (list f1 f2 f3 f4 f5)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(map entity/pos (list leader f1 f2 f3 f4 f5))
```

[VISUAL: A leader moves slowly downward. Five followers converge from all directions, their trails curving toward the leader. By the end, all followers are clustered near the leader.]

All five recalculate their velocity toward the leader every frame. They form a moving cluster.

---

## Flocking separation (avoid crowding)

Each entity steers *away* from nearby entities to maintain personal space. This is one component of flocking behavior.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'bird 0 0))
(define b (world/spawn 'bird 0.3 0.2))
(define c (world/spawn 'bird -0.2 0.1))
(entity/set-vel! a 1 0)
(entity/set-vel! b 1 0)
(entity/set-vel! c 1 0)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (for-each
     (lambda (self)
       (let ((sep-x 0) (sep-y 0))
         (for-each
          (lambda (other)
            (when (not (eq? self other))
              (let* ((self-pos (entity/pos self))
                     (other-pos (entity/pos other))
                     (dx (- (car self-pos) (car other-pos)))
                     (dy (- (cadr self-pos) (cadr other-pos)))
                     (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
                (when (< dist 1.0)
                  (set! sep-x (+ sep-x dx))
                  (set! sep-y (+ sep-y dy))))))
          (list a b c))
         (let ((v (entity/vel self)))
           (entity/set-vel! self (+ (car v) (* 0.1 sep-x)) (+ (cadr v) (* 0.1 sep-y))))))
     (list a b c))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(map entity/pos (list a b c))
```

[VISUAL: Three birds start clustered, all moving right. Their trails gradually spread apart as they repel each other. By the end, they're more evenly spaced.]

Each bird calculates the average vector *away from* nearby birds and nudges its velocity in that direction. They spread out while still moving generally rightward.

---

## Alignment (match neighbors' velocity)

Each entity adjusts its velocity to match the average velocity of nearby entities. They synchronize.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'bird -2 1))
(define b (world/spawn 'bird -2 0))
(define c (world/spawn 'bird -2 -1))
(entity/set-vel! a 2 0.5)
(entity/set-vel! b 1.5 -0.3)
(entity/set-vel! c 2.5 0.2)
(let loop ((n 80))
  (when (> n 0)
    (for-each
     (lambda (self)
       (let ((avg-vx 0) (avg-vy 0) (count 0))
         (for-each
          (lambda (other)
            (let* ((self-pos (entity/pos self))
                   (other-pos (entity/pos other))
                   (dx (- (car other-pos) (car self-pos)))
                   (dy (- (cadr other-pos) (cadr self-pos)))
                   (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
              (when (< dist 2.0)
                (let ((ov (entity/vel other)))
                  (set! avg-vx (+ avg-vx (car ov)))
                  (set! avg-vy (+ avg-vy (cadr ov)))
                  (set! count (+ count 1))))))
          (list a b c))
         (when (> count 0)
           (let ((v (entity/vel self)))
             (entity/set-vel! self 
                              (+ (* 0.95 (car v)) (* 0.05 (/ avg-vx count)))
                              (+ (* 0.95 (cadr v)) (* 0.05 (/ avg-vy count))))))))
     (list a b c))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(map entity/vel (list a b c))
```

[VISUAL: Three birds start with different velocities (different trail angles and spacings). Over time, their trails become more parallel—they're converging toward the same velocity.]

Each bird blends 5% of the average neighbor velocity into its own. After many frames, they all move together.

---

## Cohesion (steer toward the center of the group)

Each entity steers toward the average position of nearby entities. They cluster.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'bird -3 2))
(define b (world/spawn 'bird 3 -1))
(define c (world/spawn 'bird 0 -3))
(entity/set-vel! a 1 0)
(entity/set-vel! b -0.5 0.5)
(entity/set-vel! c 0 1)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (for-each
     (lambda (self)
       (let ((avg-x 0) (avg-y 0) (count 0))
         (for-each
          (lambda (other)
            (let ((opos (entity/pos other)))
              (set! avg-x (+ avg-x (car opos)))
              (set! avg-y (+ avg-y (cadr opos)))
              (set! count (+ count 1))))
          (list a b c))
         (let* ((center-x (/ avg-x count))
                (center-y (/ avg-y count))
                (self-pos (entity/pos self))
                (dx (- center-x (car self-pos)))
                (dy (- center-y (cadr self-pos)))
                (v (entity/vel self)))
           (entity/set-vel! self (+ (car v) (* 0.02 dx)) (+ (cadr v) (* 0.02 dy))))))
     (list a b c))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(map entity/pos (list a b c))
```

[VISUAL: Three birds start far apart. Their trails curve toward each other. By the end, they're clustered in the middle of the frame.]

Each bird calculates the centroid of the group and steers gently toward it. They form a flock.

---

## Full flocking (separation + alignment + cohesion)

Combine all three behaviors. The result is emergent flocking: the birds spread out enough to avoid collision, align their velocities, and stay together as a group.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define birds (list (world/spawn 'bird -3 2)
                    (world/spawn 'bird 3 -1)
                    (world/spawn 'bird 0 -3)
                    (world/spawn 'bird -2 -2)
                    (world/spawn 'bird 2 2)))
(for-each (lambda (b) (entity/set-vel! b 1 0.5)) birds)
(let loop ((n 120))
  (when (> n 0)
    (for-each
     (lambda (self)
       (let ((sep-x 0) (sep-y 0)
             (avg-vx 0) (avg-vy 0)
             (avg-x 0) (avg-y 0)
             (count 0))
         (for-each
          (lambda (other)
            (let* ((spos (entity/pos self))
                   (opos (entity/pos other))
                   (dx (- (car spos) (car opos)))
                   (dy (- (cadr spos) (cadr opos)))
                   (dist (dsqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))
              (when (< dist 2.0)
                (when (> dist 0.01)
                  (set! sep-x (+ sep-x (/ dx dist)))
                  (set! sep-y (+ sep-y (/ dy dist))))
                (let ((ov (entity/vel other)))
                  (set! avg-vx (+ avg-vx (car ov)))
                  (set! avg-vy (+ avg-vy (cadr ov))))
                (set! avg-x (+ avg-x (car opos)))
                (set! avg-y (+ avg-y (cadr opos)))
                (set! count (+ count 1)))))
          birds)
         (when (> count 0)
           (let* ((center-x (/ avg-x count))
                  (center-y (/ avg-y count))
                  (spos (entity/pos self))
                  (coh-x (- center-x (car spos)))
                  (coh-y (- center-y (cadr spos)))
                  (v (entity/vel self))
                  (vx (car v))
                  (vy (cadr v)))
             (entity/set-vel! self 
                              (+ vx (* 0.05 sep-x) (* 0.02 (/ avg-vx count)) (* 0.01 coh-x))
                              (+ vy (* 0.05 sep-y) (* 0.02 (/ avg-vy count)) (* 0.01 coh-y)))))))
     birds)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(map entity/pos birds))
```

[VISUAL: Five birds start scattered. Their trails show them spreading slightly (separation), then curving together (cohesion), and aligning into parallel motion (alignment). By the end, they move as a coordinated flock.]

This is Craig Reynolds's classic boids algorithm, implemented as velocity adjustments. The birds self-organize into a flock. It's emergent behavior from simple rules.

---

## Velocity as a signal

Sometimes you don't care about the *position* an entity reaches—you care about its *velocity* as a carrier of information. For example, a windvane entity could have its velocity set to match the wind direction, so other systems can read it.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define windvane (world/spawn 'vane 0 0))
(define leaf (world/spawn 'leaf -2 1))
(entity/set-vel! windvane 2 -1)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((wind (entity/vel windvane)))
      (entity/set-vel! leaf (car wind) (cadr wind)))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos leaf)
```

[VISUAL: The windvane is invisible or static—it doesn't move visibly. The leaf, however, drifts in the direction the windvane's velocity points. Final position of leaf is around (1.92, 0.04).]

The windvane's *velocity* is the wind vector. The leaf copies it. This is a way to broadcast a direction/speed to other entities without using a separate data structure.

---

## Speed limiting (clamping velocity magnitude)

Calculate the current speed. If it exceeds a maximum, scale the velocity down to that max.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define ship (world/spawn 'ship 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! ship 3 4)
(let ((max-speed 3.5))
  (let loop ((n 50))
    (when (> n 0)
      (let* ((v (entity/vel ship))
             (vx (car v))
             (vy (cadr v))
             (speed (dsqrt (+ (* vx vx) (* vy vy)))))
        (when (> speed max-speed)
          (let ((scale (/ max-speed speed)))
            (entity/set-vel! ship (* vx scale) (* vy scale)))))
      (world/step 0.016)
      (loop (- n 1)))))
(entity/pos ship)
```

[VISUAL: The ship tries to move at speed 5 (sqrt(3² + 4²)), but the limiter clamps it to 3.5. The trail is in the same direction as the original velocity, but shorter—moving slower than requested.]

We calculate speed = sqrt(vx² + vy²). If speed > max, we scale both components by (max / speed). The direction stays the same; the magnitude is clamped.

---

## Velocity in polar coordinates (magnitude and angle)

Store velocity as a speed and a heading, update them independently, then convert to Cartesian each frame.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define comet (world/spawn 'comet -4 -3))
(let ((speed 3.0) (heading 45))
  (let loop ((n 80))
    (when (> n 0)
      (let ((angle (* heading (/ PI 180))))
        (entity/set-vel! comet (* speed (dcos angle)) (* speed (dsin angle))))
      (set! heading (+ heading 2))
      (world/step 0.016)
      (loop (- n 1)))))
(entity/pos comet)
```

[VISUAL: A comet spirals outward. The trail is a smooth curve—each frame the heading rotates 2 degrees while speed stays constant. Final position is back near the start (because 80 steps × 2°/step = 160°, not quite a full rotation).]

We store heading as a mutable angle, increment it each frame, and convert to vx/vy with trig. This is cleaner than manually rotating a Cartesian vector when you're thinking in angles.

---

## Velocity field visualization (no entity, just the field)

Spawn many stationary entities in a grid, set each one's velocity to a function of its position (e.g., a vortex), and visualize the result. They don't move—just display the field.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(let ((x-start -3) (x-end 3) (y-start -3) (y-end 3) (step 0.8))
  (let outer ((x x-start))
    (when (<= x x-end)
      (let inner ((y y-start))
        (when (<= y y-end)
          (let* ((marker (world/spawn 'arrow x y))
                 (angle (datan2 y x))
                 (speed 1.5))
            (entity/set-vel! marker 
                             (* speed (- (dsin angle)))
                             (* speed (dcos angle))))
          (inner (+ y step))))
      (outer (+ x step)))))
(world/step 0.016)
(world/count)
```

[VISUAL: A grid of arrows, each pointing perpendicular to the radius from the origin (a vortex field). The arrows don't move—they're just placed to show the velocity at each point in space.]

This is how you visualize a vector field. Each arrow's velocity *represents* the field at that location, even though the arrows themselves are stationary.

---

## Zero velocity initialization (stateful entities that aren't moving yet)

Sometimes you spawn an entity but don't want it to move until triggered. Set velocity to (0, 0) initially, then activate later.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define sleeper (world/spawn 'sleeper 0 0))
(entity/set-vel! sleeper 0 0)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/set-vel! sleeper 4 2)
(let loop ((n 30))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(entity/pos sleeper)
```

[VISUAL: The entity stays at the origin for the first half. Then suddenly it springs to life and moves diagonally. The trail has a long stationary segment, then a diagonal line.]

Velocity (0, 0) is a valid state. The entity exists, responds to queries, but doesn't move until you give it a nonzero velocity.

---

## Hand-off (one entity stops, another starts)

Two entities. The first moves, then stops and sets the second's velocity to its own final velocity. The motion \"transfers.\"

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define runner-a (world/spawn 'runner -4 0))
(define runner-b (world/spawn 'runner -2 0))
(entity/set-vel! runner-a 3 0)
(entity/set-vel! runner-b 0 0)
(let loop ((n 40))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(let ((v (entity/vel runner-a)))
  (entity/set-vel! runner-a 0 0)
  (entity/set-vel! runner-b (car v) (cadr v)))
(let loop ((n 40))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos runner-a) (entity/pos runner-b))
```

[VISUAL: Runner A moves right, then stops. At that moment, runner B (who was stationary) starts moving at the same speed. It's like passing a baton—one trail ends, another begins, same velocity.]

This is a *relay*. The velocity is copied from one entity to another. The motion continues, but the actor changes.

---

## Velocity as a ray (collision detection preview)

Cast an entity forward at high speed for one frame, check what it overlaps, then reset it. This is a poor-man's raycast.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define caster (world/spawn 'ray-origin 0 0))
(define target (world/spawn 'target 3 0.2))
(entity/set-vel! caster 100 0)
(world/step 0.001)
(let ((hit (entity/overlaps? caster target)))
  (entity/set-pos! caster 0 0)
  (entity/set-vel! caster 0 0)
  hit)
```

[VISUAL: Conceptual diagram: a ray shoots out from the origin, passes through the target. The overlap is detected. The caster is then reset to the origin.]

We move the caster very fast for a very short time, check for overlaps, then reset. This simulates a raycast. (A real raycast would be a dedicated verb, but this shows that velocity can be a *geometric query tool*, not just motion.)

<!-- BUILD: world/raycast verb for proper raycasting -->

---

## Velocity symmetry (two entities, mirrored velocities)

Two entities moving in exactly opposite directions, same speed. They're symmetric around a midpoint.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define left (world/spawn 'particle -2 0))
(define right (world/spawn 'particle 2 0))
(entity/set-vel! left 1.5 1)
(entity/set-vel! right -1.5 -1)
(let loop ((n 60))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos left) (entity/pos right))
```

[VISUAL: Two particles move in opposite directions. Their trails are mirror images. They start symmetric around (0,0) and end symmetric around (0,0), just farther apart.]

The midpoint between them stays at (0, 0) because their velocities are equal and opposite. This is useful for paired animations—two halves of a split, two wings of a bird, etc.

---

## Thruster pulses (velocity added in bursts)

Instead of setting velocity, *add* a fixed impulse every N frames. The entity accelerates in steps.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define ship (world/spawn 'ship -5 0))
(entity/set-vel! ship 0 0)
(let loop ((n 100) (frame 0))
  (when (> n 0)
    (when (= (modulo frame 15) 0)
      (let ((v (entity/vel ship)))
        (entity/set-vel! ship (+ (car v) 0.5) (cadr v))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1) (+ frame 1))))
(entity/pos ship)
```

[VISUAL: A spaceship accelerates in discrete jumps. The trail has visible \"steps\"—segments where speed is constant, then a jump to a faster segment. Final position shows it traveled far due to repeated acceleration.]

Every 15 frames we add 0.5 to vx. The ship jolts forward repeatedly. This is how you simulate a pulsed thruster or stamina-based dash.

---

## Velocity inheritance (child entity starts with parent's velocity)

Spawn a projectile from a moving entity. Give the projectile the parent's current velocity *plus* a firing velocity.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define ship (world/spawn 'ship -3 1))
(entity/set-vel! ship 2 0.5)
(let loop ((n 20))
  (when (> n 0)
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(let* ((ship-pos (entity/pos ship))
       (ship-vel (entity/vel ship))
       (bullet (world/spawn 'bullet (car ship-pos) (cadr ship-pos))))
  (entity/set-vel! bullet (+ (car ship-vel) 5) (+ (cadr ship-vel) 0))
  (let loop ((n 40))
    (when (> n 0)
      (world/step 0.016)
      (loop (- n 1))))
  (list (entity/pos ship) (entity/pos bullet)))
```

[VISUAL: A ship moves diagonally. Midway through, a bullet spawns from it. The bullet's trail continues the ship's diagonal but at a steeper angle (because we added 5 to vx). By the end, the bullet is well ahead.]

The bullet inherits the ship's velocity and adds its own muzzle velocity. This is how you fire from a moving platform—the projectile carries the platform's momentum.

---

## Momentum transfer (elastic collision, simplified)

Two entities collide head-on. Swap their velocities (simplified elastic collision in 1D).

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(define a (world/spawn 'ball -2 0))
(define b (world/spawn 'ball 2 0))
(entity/set-vel! a 3 0)
(entity/set-vel! b -2 0)
(let loop ((n 100))
  (when (> n 0)
    (let ((dist (entity/distance a b)))
      (when (< dist 0.5)
        (let ((va (entity/vel a))
              (vb (entity/vel b)))
          (entity/set-vel! a (car vb) (cadr vb))
          (entity/set-vel! b (car va) (cadr va)))))
    (world/step 0.016)
    (loop (- n 1))))
(list (entity/pos a) (entity/pos b))
```

[VISUAL: Two balls approach each other. When they get close, they bounce—their trails reverse direction instantly. The trails show a sharp V at the collision point. Final positions have the balls moving apart.]

When distance < 0.5, we swap velocities. This simulates a perfect elastic collision in 1D (ignoring actual physics for simplicity). It's a velocity-based interaction.

---

## Exercises

Here are six scenarios to implement as complete Motoi Scheme programs. Use the patterns and verbs you've learned in this chapter.

**1. The Crossing**  
Spawn four entities at the corners of a square (e.g., (-3, -3), (3, -3), (3, 3), (-3, 3)). Give each a velocity that sends it toward the *opposite* corner. All four pass through the center at the same time. Run for 100 frames and report final positions.

**2. The Spiral Outward**  
Spawn an entity at (1, 0). Each frame, rotate its velocity by 3 degrees (convert current velocity to angle, add 3°, convert back to Cartesian) and increase its speed by 0.02. Run for 200 frames. The entity should spiral outward. Report final position and visualize the trail.

**3. The Swarm**  
Spawn 10 entities at random positions within (-2, -2) to (2, 2). Give each a random velocity (magnitude between 0.5 and 2, random angle). Every 20 frames, nudge each entity's velocity slightly toward the centroid of all 10. Run for 150 frames. They should loosely cluster while still moving. Report the final spread (max distance between any two).

**4. The Pong Ball**  
Spawn a ball at (0, 0) with velocity (3, 2). When it hits the left or right wall (x = ±5), negate vx. When it hits the top or bottom wall (y = ±3), negate vy. Run for 300 frames and count how many times it bounced (hint: track when a component flips sign).

**5. The Carrier and Drones**  
Spawn a carrier at (-5, 0) moving at (2, 0.5). Spawn three drones at positions offset from the carrier (e.g., carrier + (0, 1), carrier + (1, -1), carrier + (-1, 0)). Each frame, set


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### Moving Along One Axis

The simplest case: an entity moves horizontally across the canvas at constant speed.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((x (+ 50 (* t 80))))
    (world
      (entity 'dot
              (placement x 240)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 12 '#x333333))))))
```

[VISUAL: A dark gray circle sliding smoothly from left to right, starting at x=50 when t=0 and reaching x=130 at t=1.]

The position `x` is a **linear function of time**: `x = 50 + 80t`. At t=0, x=50. At t=1, x=130. The velocity is 80 pixels per second.

---

Now vertical motion: a balloon rises.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((y (- 400 (* t 120))))
    (world
      (entity 'balloon
              (placement 240 y)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 16 '#xFF6B6B)
                (rect -2 16 4 30 '#x8B4513))))))
```

[VISUAL: A red balloon with a brown string drifting upward, starting near the bottom of the canvas and climbing toward the top.]

Subtracting makes the balloon rise: as `t` increases, `y` decreases. Velocity is −120 pixels per second.

---

A slow drift versus a quick dash:

```scheme
(define (route-slow t)
  (world
    (entity 'dot
            (placement (* t 40) 200)
            (shapes
              (circle 0 0 8 '#x4A90E2)))))

(define (route-fast t)
  (world
    (entity 'dot
            (placement (* t 240) 200)
            (shapes
              (circle 0 0 8 '#xE24A4A)))))

(route-fast 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: Two side-by-side renders. The slow route shows a blue dot that has moved 20 pixels at t=0.5. The fast route shows a red dot that has moved 120 pixels in the same time.]

Same time, different velocities. The red dot's velocity is six times the blue's.

---


### Moving Along Two Axes

Horizontal and vertical motion combine to produce diagonal travel.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((x (+ 100 (* t 160)))
        (y (+ 100 (* t 120))))
    (world
      (entity 'mover
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (rect -10 -10 20 20 '#x2ECC71))))))
```

[VISUAL: A green square gliding diagonally from upper-left toward lower-right.]

The entity moves 160 px/s horizontally and 120 px/s vertically. The **speed** (magnitude of velocity) is `sqrt(160² + 120²) = 200` px/s. The **direction** is the angle `atan(120/160)` ≈ 36.9°.

---

Converging paths: two entities move toward the same point.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((x1 (- 120 (* t 100)))
        (x2 (+ 360 (* t -100)))
        (y1 (+ 100 (* t 140)))
        (y2 (+ 380 (* t -140))))
    (world
      (entity 'left
              (placement x1 y1)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 10 '#xF39C12)))
      (entity 'right
              (placement x2 y2)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 10 '#x9B59B6))))))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle descending from upper-left and a purple circle ascending from lower-right, both heading toward the center of the canvas.]

At t=0.5, both entities meet near (70, 170). Their velocities are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction.

---

A figure-eight pattern built from independent x and y motion with different rates:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((theta (* t 6.28318))
        (x (+ 240 (* 100 (sin theta))))
        (y (+ 240 (* 80 (sin (* 2 theta))))))
    (world
      (entity 'tracer
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 6 '#xE74C3C))))))
```

[VISUAL: A red dot tracing a horizontal figure-eight path, looping smoothly through two symmetrical curves.]

The x-coordinate oscillates once per cycle; y oscillates twice, producing the crossed loops.

---


### Encoding Direction: Angle and Speed

Instead of separate x and y velocities, we can specify a **heading** (angle) and a **speed** (magnitude), then decompose into components.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((angle 0.785398)  ; 45 degrees in radians
         (speed 150)
         (vx (* speed (cos angle)))
         (vy (* speed (sin angle)))
         (x (+ 100 (* t vx)))
         (y (+ 100 (* t vy))))
    (world
      (entity 'dart
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (polygon (list -8 0  8 0  0 -16) '#x3498DB))))))
```

[VISUAL: A blue triangle (pointing up-right) moving diagonally at 45° from the starting corner.]

The angle 0.785398 rad = 45°. Speed 150 px/s splits into vx ≈ 106 and vy ≈ 106.

---

A steeper climb:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((angle 1.308997)  ; 75 degrees
         (speed 120)
         (vx (* speed (cos angle)))
         (vy (* speed (sin angle)))
         (x (+ 240 (* t vx)))
         (y (+ 400 (* t (- vy)))))
    (world
      (entity 'climber
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (rect -6 -12 12 24 '#x1ABC9C))))))
```

[VISUAL: A teal rectangle rising steeply upward from the bottom center, moving mostly vertically with a slight rightward drift.]

At 75°, the vertical component dominates. The rectangle climbs faster than it drifts.

---


### Wrapping and Looping

An entity that exits one edge and re-enters the opposite: classic arcade wrap-around.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((raw-x (+ 50 (* t 200)))
         (x (modulo raw-x 480)))
    (world
      (entity 'orbiter
              (placement x 240)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 14 '#xE67E22))))))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle moving left-to-right. When it exits the right edge, it instantly reappears at the left edge and continues.]

The `modulo` function wraps x into [0, 480). The entity loops horizontally forever.

---

Vertical wrap-around, faster:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((raw-y (+ 0 (* t 300)))
         (y (modulo raw-y 480)))
    (world
      (entity 'riser
              (placement 240 y)
              (shapes
                (rect -10 -10 20 20 '#x8E44AD))))))
```

[VISUAL: A purple square rising from top to bottom, wrapping continuously at 300 px/s.]

---


### Parallel Lanes

Multiple entities moving at different speeds in parallel lanes:

