### Lissajous Figures

Combining two perpendicular oscillations at different frequencies:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((cx 240)
         (cy 240)
         (a 100)
         (b 100)
         (fx 2.0)
         (fy 3.0)
         (theta (* t 6.28318))
         (x (+ cx (* a (sin (* fx theta)))))
         (y (+ cy (* b (sin (* fy theta))))))
    (world
      (entity 'lissajous
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 6 '#x2ECC71))))))
```

[VISUAL: A green circle tracing a complex looping pattern (Lissajous curve) with a 2:3 frequency ratio.]

Frequency ratio 2:3 produces a characteristic pretzel-like path.

---


### Speed and Distance

Two entities leaving the same point at different speeds: the faster one covers more ground.

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let ((angle 0.5236)
        (speed-slow 60)
        (speed-fast 140))
    (world
      (entity 'slow-mover
              (placement (* t speed-slow (cos angle))
                         (* t speed-slow (sin angle)))
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 8 '#xBDC3C7)))
      (entity 'fast-mover
              (placement (* t speed-fast (cos angle))
                         (* t speed-fast (sin angle)))
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 8 '#x2C3E50))))))
```

[VISUAL: Two circles moving along the same diagonal path. The dark circle pulls ahead steadily, its distance from the origin increasing faster.]

At any time t, the distance ratio equals the speed ratio: 140/60 ≈ 2.33.

---


### Velocity Decomposition in a Triangle

An entity moving at a given speed along a line defined by two points:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((x0 100)
         (y0 150)
         (x1 400)
         (y1 300)
         (dx (- x1 x0))
         (dy (- y1 y0))
         (dist (sqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy))))
         (ux (/ dx dist))
         (uy (/ dy dist))
         (speed 110)
         (x (+ x0 (* t speed ux)))
         (y (+ y0 (* t speed uy))))
    (world
      (entity 'traveler
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 7 '#xE74C3C))))))
```

[VISUAL: A red circle moving from point (100, 150) toward point (400, 300) along a straight line at 110 px/s.]

The unit vector `(ux, uy)` gives direction; multiplying by speed and time gives displacement.

---


### Following a Piecewise Path

An entity that travels one direction, then another, based on elapsed time:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((segment-duration 1.0)
         (phase (modulo t (* 2 segment-duration)))
         (v 100)
         (x (if (< phase segment-duration)
                (* phase v)
                v))
         (y (if (< phase segment-duration)
                0
                (* (- phase segment-duration) v))))
    (world
      (entity 'corner-turner
              (placement x y)
              (shapes
                (rect -8 -8 16 16 '#x16A085))))))
```

[VISUAL: A teal square moving horizontally for 1 second, then turning 90° and moving vertically for 1 second, then wrapping back to the start.]

Piecewise constant velocity: horizontal in phase 1, vertical in phase 2.

---


### Bouncing Between Walls (Continuous Model)

An entity reflecting off vertical boundaries:

```scheme
(define (route t)
  (let* ((period 3.0)
         (phase (modulo t period))
         (v 160)
         (x-left 40)
         (x-right 440)
         (x-range (- x-right x-left))
         (raw-x (* phase v))
         (bounces (floor (/ raw-x x-range)))
         (x-in-range (modulo raw-x x-range))
         (x (if (even? bounces)
                (+ x-left x-in-range)
                (- x-right x-in-range))))
    (world
      (entity 'bouncer
              (placement x 240)
              (shapes
                (circle 0 0 10 '#xF4D03F))))))
```

[VISUAL: A yellow circle bouncing left and right between two invisible vertical walls, reversing direction at each boundary.]

Velocity magnitude stays 160 px/s; direction flips at walls.

